"{\"paper\": {\"status\": \"map_review\", \"title\": \"Kneser-Ney Smoothing on Expected Counts\", \"url\": \"http://www.aclweb.org/anthology/P14-1072\", \"abstract\": \"Widely used in speech and language processing, Kneser-Ney (KN) smoothing has consistently been shown to be one of the best-performing smoothing methods.However, KN smoothing assumes integer counts, limiting its potential uses\\u2014for example, inside Expectation-Maximization.In this paper, we propose a generalization of KN smoothing that operates on fractional counts, or, more precisely, on distributions over counts.We rederive all the steps of KN smoothing to operate on count distributions instead of integral counts, and apply it to two tasks where KN smoothing was not applicable before: one in language model adaptation, and the other in word alignment.In both cases, our method improves performance significantly.\\n\", \"field\": \"Machine Translation\", \"user\": \"MT-admin_Hui_Zhang\"}, \"map_name\": \"Kneser-Ney_Smoothing_1.html\", \"_id\": {\"$oid\": \"5858b889dc9e6c4509cf039d\"}, \"annotation\": {\"metrics\": [{\"type\": \"Quantitative\", \"name\": \"machine translation (MT)_BLEU\", \"task_name\": {\"name\": \"machine translation (MT)\"}, \"measure\": \"BLEU\"}, {\"type\": \"Qualitative\", \"name\": \"language model domain adaptation_quality\", \"task_name\": {\"name\": \"language model domain adaptation\"}, \"measure\": \"quality\"}, {\"type\": \"Qualitative\", \"name\": \"word alignment_quality\", \"task_name\": {\"name\": \"word alignment\"}, \"measure\": \"quality\"}, {\"type\": \"Qualitative\", \"name\": \"machine translation (MT)_quality\", \"task_name\": {\"name\": \"machine translation (MT)\"}, \"measure\": \"quality\"}], \"tasks\": [{\"name\": \"smoothing\"}, {\"name\": \"none (baseline)\"}, {\"name\": \"variational Bayes - Riley and Gildea, 2012\"}, {\"name\": \"fractional WB\"}, {\"name\": \"fractional KN\"}, {\"name\": \"expected KN\"}, {\"name\": \"interpolation with the unigram d